PVS-Studio is a static code analyzer and SAST (static application security
testing) tool that is available for C and C++ desktop and embedded development,
C# and Java under Windows, Linux and macOS.

Usage: pvs-studio-analyzer analyze [-l <FILE>] [-j <N>] [-i] [-o <FILE>]
                           [-c <FILE>] [-s <FILE>] [-q] [-f <FILE>]
                           [-S <FILE>] [-C <COMPILER_NAME[=COMPILER_TYPE]...>]
                           [-E <VAR=VALUE>] [-e <DIR>] [-a <MODE>] [-r <DIR>]
                           [-d] [--preprocessor <NAME>] [--platform <NAME>]
                           [--ignore-ccache] [-R <FILE>]
                           [--analyze-specified-system-paths] [--intermodular]
                           [-A <FILE>] [--regenerate-depend-info]
                           [--regenerate-depend-info-without-analysis]

Launch PVS-Studio for your project

Options:

    -l [FILE], --lic-file [FILE]
        PVS-Studio license file
        Default: ""
    -j [N], --threads [N]
        Allow N PVS-Studio analyzers at once
        Default: 1
    -i, --incremental
        Use incremental analysis
    -o [FILE], --output-file [FILE]
        Place the analyzer's report into FILE
    -c [FILE], --cfg [FILE]
        Run PVS using config FILE
        Default: ""
    -s [FILE], --suppress-file [FILE]
        Path to suppress file
        Default:
        "/home/user/Documents/Projects/Cpp/qTox/suppress_file.suppress.json"
    -q, --quiet
        Analysis progress is not displayed
    -f [FILE], --file [FILE]
        Use trace output or compile commands database FILE
        Default: 'compile_commands.json', 'strace_out'
    -S [FILE], --source-files [FILE]
        Allows to analyze a list of source files, taking into account compile
        dependencies. The list of files is plaintext, with every file on a
        separate line, absolute or relative paths.
    -C [COMPILER_NAME[=COMPILER_TYPE]...], --compiler
    [COMPILER_NAME[=COMPILER_TYPE]...]
        Filtering compiler commands by the compiler name, with the ability to
        explicitly specify the compiler type. Supported compiler types: gcc,
        clang, keil5, keil5gnu, keil6, tiarmcgt, cl, clangcl, gccarm,
        iararm_v7_orolder, iararm, qcc, xc8. If a compiler type is not
        specified, the compiler found will be treated as derived from GCC.
    -E [VAR=VALUE], --env [VAR=VALUE]
        Modify environment for preprocessor
    -e [DIR], --exclude-path [DIR]
        Directory whose files are not necessary to check
    -a [MODE], --analysis-mode [MODE]
        MODE defines the group of warnings that will be activated during
        analysis:
        64 - 64-bit errors;
        GA - General Analysis;
        OP - Micro-optimizations;
        CS - Customers Specific Requests;
        MISRA - MISRA guidelines;
        AUTOSAR - AUTOSAR guidelines;
        OWASP - OWASP guidelines.
        Several types of warnings must be separated by ';', e.g. 'GA;OP;64'.
        Default: GA
    -r [DIR], --sourcetree-root [DIR]
        Replace absolute paths in report with relative paths
        Default: ""
    -d, --disableLicenseExpirationCheck
        Sets return code back to 0 if license will expire soon
    --preprocessor [NAME]
        Preprocessor (gcc or clang)
        Default: <auto-detected>
    --platform [NAME]
        Platform (linux64, linux32)
        Default: linux64
    --ignore-ccache
        Enables the analysis of all source files ignoring the current ccache
        state. Even if ccache decides that compiler should not run, the
        analyzer will still analyze the corresponding source files.
    -R [FILE], --rules-config [FILE]
        Path to the diagnostic configuration file (.pvsconfig)
    --analyze-specified-system-paths
        Enables the analysis of files inside directories specified by the
        following compiler flags: 'isystem', 'isysroot', 'system_include_dir'
        etc.
    --intermodular
        C++ intermodular mode performs deeper code analysis at the cost of a
        longer analysis time
    -A [FILE], --annotation-file [FILE]
        Specifies a path to annotation json file (*.json).
    These flags cannot be used at the same time. Use only one of
    them.
      --regenerate-depend-info
          Regenerates compilation dependency information for each source file
          and saves it into depend_info.json.
      --regenerate-depend-info-without-analysis
          Regenerates compilation dependency information for each source file
          and saves it into depend_info.json. When this flag is used, the
          analysis will not be performed.

